  "text": "The Loki client implementations in Grafana are found under pkg/components/loki/ with two distinct implementations: HTTP and gRPC.\n\nHTTP CLIENT CONFIGURATION:\nThe HTTP client retry and timeout logic is primarily defined in pkg/components/loki/lokihttp/client.go and pkg/components/loki/lokihttp/config.go. The Config struct (config.go:19-20) contains BackoffConfig and Timeout fields. In client.go, the sendBatch() function (line 290) implements the retry logic using backoff.New() (line 299) and backoff.Ongoing() (line 318) to control retries for HTTP 429, 5xx status codes, and connection-level errors. The StopNow() method (line 376) cancels the context to stop ongoing HTTP requests and retry loops. The Stop() method (line 370) gracefully closes the entry channel. The Timeout is set on the HTTP client at line 175 (c.client.Timeout = cfg.Timeout) and used in request context at line 331 with context.WithTimeout().\n\nFor testing/mocking, the fake.go file implements the Client interface with stub implementations of StopNow() and Stop() methods.\n\ngRPC CLIENT CONFIGURATION:\nThe gRPC client retry and timeout configuration is in pkg/components/loki/lokigrpc/client.go and pkg/components/loki/lokigrpc/config.go. The Config struct (config.go:9-10) defines Retries and Timeout fields. In client.go, the grpcRetryOption() function (line 82) configures gRPC retry behavior using grpcretry.WithMax(c.cfg.Retries) (line 85) to set the maximum number of retries. The timeoutCtx() function (line 90) creates a context with timeout (line 92) using context.WithTimeout() when cfg.Timeout > 0, or a cancellable context otherwise. These retry and timeout mechanisms are applied during client initialization in the init() function (line 57) which adds the retry interceptor to gRPC dial options."
}

